@InProceedings{AnggorojatiMahallePrasadEtAl2012,
  author       = {Anggorojati, Bayu and Mahalle, Parikshit Narendra and Prasad, Neeli Rashmi and Prasad, Ramjee},
  title        = {{Capability-based access control delegation model on the federated IoT network}},
  booktitle    = {Wireless Personal Multimedia Communications (WPMC), 2012 15th International Symposium on},
  year         = {2012},
  pages        = {604--608},
  organization = {IEEE},
  abstract     = {Flexibility is an important property for general
access control system and especially in the Internet of Things
(IoT), which can be achieved by access or authority delegation.
Delegation mechanisms in access control that have been studied
until now have been intended mainly for a system that has no
resource constraint, such as a web-based system, which is not
very suitable for a highly pervasive system such as IoT. To
this end, this paper presents an access delegation method with
security considerations based on Capability-based Context Aware
Access Control (CCAAC) model intended for federated machine-
to-machine communication or IoT networks. The main idea of
our proposed model is that the access delegation is realized by
means of a capability propagation mechanism, and incorporating
the context information as well as secure capability propagation
under federated IoT environments. By using the identity-based
capability-based access control approach as well as contextual
information and secure federated IoT, this proposed model
provides scalability and flexibility as well as secure authority
delegation for highly distributed system.},
  comment      = {enphases on lightweight and flexible
Federated IoT : 
We want same identity cross domain. A domain is made up of several clusters managed by the same entity. 
proposes new access control model with build-in delegation : CCAAC (Capability-based Context Aware Access Control)


Anggorojati et al.~\cite{AnggorojatiMahallePrasadEtAl2012} focus on delegation
in the context of federated-IoT. They define an IoT domain as clusters of 
devices managed by the same entity. Domains can federate to allow for the 
management of a subject's identity across several of them. Being in the IoT, the
subject is a device and the interactions take the form of device-to-device
communication. For that reason, the authors use concepts and models developed 
in~\cite{prasad2010my}, such as PN.

Capabilities are used to carry permissions that are given under contextual 
conditions. Given examples of context are time, location, authentication or 
trust level. Capabilities here are descriptive and tied to the subject they 
have been created for. They are of two types: internal and external.
Internal capabilities are given to subjects that request access to an object 
belonging to the same security domain as themselves. When a subject wants to 
access an object outside of its security domain, it must obtain an external 
capability through delegation.

Let $A$, $B$ be two security domains, and $s_A$, $s_B$ subjects of $A$ and $B$
respectively. Let $O$ be an object of $A$. $s_A$ has the necessary privileges to
perform some actions on $O$. For $s_B$ to be able to access $O$, $s_A$ can 
delegate its privileges to it. To that hand, $s_A$, the delegator, sends a 
delegation request to domain $A$'s IoT Federation Manager(IoT-FM). The IoT-FM's 
role is to manage its domain participation in the federation. This include 
ruling on delegation requests. The request is checked against policies and
context. If granted, the IoT-FM of domain $A$ will produce and external 
capability for $s_B$, the delegatee, and send it back to $s_A$. Communicating 
the capability to $s_B$ is left at the charge of $s_A$.

Here, each domain's IoT-FM plays the role of a PDP. When presented with an 
access request, the end-device checks the capability that was sent along. It must
come from its domain's IoT-FM. Some local conditions might need to be checked as
well. The paper present a model and therefore stay at a really high level 
when describing the solution. No implementation has been realized.

This solution presents a high degree of usability as a subject only has to 
manage its identity in one security domain while still being able to access 
services living in others. For the same reason, it scales well in the number of
federated domains. Inside a single domain however, the PDP function is 
centralized and policies might get more complex with each new domain entering 
the federation.

Revocation is not addressed, neither explicitly nor implicitly. We can however 
suppose that capabilities have a limited lifetime. Under this assumption, the 
PDP is not needed for each access and the maintaining the system becomes easier.

As only the model is presented, it is left to the implementers to decide the 
degree of granularity. It is possible to define privileges at the resource level.},
  file         = {:Articles/2012_Anggorojati_Capability-based access control delegation model on the federated IoT network.pdf:PDF},
  keywords     = {capability-based access control, delegation, security, IoT},
  timestamp    = {2019-01-16},
  url          = {http://vbn.aau.dk/files/73429266/CAP_DELEGATION_WPMC.pdf},
}

