@Article{BentovLeeMizrahiEtAl2014,
  author        = {Bentov, Iddo and Lee, Charles and Mizrahi, Alex and Rosenfeld, Meni},
  title         = {Proof of Activity: Extending Bitcoin's Proof of Work via Proof of Stake},
  journal       = {ACM SIGMETRICS Performance Evaluation Review},
  year          = {2014},
  volume        = {42},
  number        = {3},
  pages         = {34--37},
  __markedentry = {[sophie:]},
  comment       = {The article proposes a new consensus protocol based on both PoW and PoS. They are concerned with the attack environment of cryptocurrencies after the original money supply has been distributed and the only reward for block creation comes from transaction fees.
They find that PoW miners might not have a strong enough incentive to maintain the security of the network as coins they mine might be exchanged for other currency and mining hardware can be re-purposed for other crypto-currency. Stakeholders are more invested in the system. The proposed Proof of Activity however requires more rounds of communication and more involvment.

The authors start by examining three ways in which PoW mining post minting is subject to the tragedy of the commons. The first concerns the willingness of users to pay transaction fees. Even if everybody agrees they must be paid to incentivize miners, it is in everyone best interest not to pay too high a fee themselves.The solution to this is to not include transactions with low fees in mined blocks. Which brings us to the second contradiction. It is in the miners best interest to agree on a minimum fee, that way people would have to pay or their transactions would never be included. However, miners that do not follow the rules will increase their profit as they will include more transactions in their blocks. A proposed solution is to add some protocol-enforced rules such as capping the number of transactions per block. This way, miners would only include the transactions with the highest fees which would force people to pay them. The problem is that the cost of protection might be more than the users are willing to pay. The last problem is that the fees are only paid to the miner that created the block when the cost of running the network are also in propagation, verification and storage and are shared amongs all the nodes. This could encourage miners to stop propagating the transactions to keep the reward for themselves. A solution would be to limit the allowed size of a block.
Other problems such as network DoS and isolation are considered to be out of the scope of the document as they apply to the different methods of consensus just the same.

Now for the protocol. $N$ stakeholders are chosen to sign empty PoW blocks (no transactions included). This selection is done by deriving a fixed number of satoshis from the PoW block. Then, invoking follow-the-satoshi, the life of the coin is traced from origin to the hand of its current owner. Each satoshi selects one signer. The first $N-1$ chosen ones simply sign. The $N$th one create the final block by including the PoW block, transactions, previous signatures and finally her own. The longest chain is still considered in terms of PoW. The fees are divided unequally among the miner, the signers and the final block creator. PoW is used mainly to slow down the block creation. It is a reward system rather than a punitive one. It incentivize people to run full nodes and participate actively in the network (hence the name).

Several add-ons are discussed. The first proposes to include PoW block that did not get sign to measure the stakeholder's participation level. The second wants to force the stakeholders to prove they are running a full node. Because people might not want to entrust the key they used to secure their money to an online application, a third add-on proposes key delegation. One could delegate the power of signing blocks to a key that cannot sign transactions. Actually, to discourage pooling, a trade-off is made where these keys can transfer all the funds to a pre-defined adress or transfer a limited amount to any adress. A final add-on is decentralized stake pools.},
  publisher     = {ACM},
  timestamp     = {2018-06-28},
  url           = {http://eprint.iacr.org/2014/452.pdf},
}

