@InProceedings{SeitzSelanderGehrmann2013,
  author       = {Seitz, Ludwig and Selander, G{\"o}ran and Gehrmann, Christian},
  title        = {Authorization framework for the internet-of-things},
  booktitle    = {World of Wireless, Mobile and Multimedia Networks (WoWMoM), 2013 IEEE 14th International Symposium and Workshops on a},
  year         = {2013},
  pages        = {1--6},
  organization = {IEEE},
  abstract     = {This paper describes a framework that allows fine-
grained and flexible access control to connected devices with very
limited processing power and memory.
We propose a set of security and performance requirements
for this setting and derive an authorization framework dis-
tributing processing costs between constrained devices and less
constrained back-end servers while keeping message exchanges
with the constrained devices at a minimum.
As a proof of concept we present performance results from
a prototype implementing the device part of the framework.},
  comment      = {This paper adresses authorization and access control in the IoT, putting an accent on the constrained component of the devices. They take the case of devices communicating with several nodes and therefore having to enforce some kind of fine grained authorization decisions. This approach is focused on using local parameters, being a generic solution and using standards optimized for constrained environmenent (no additionnal message + reasonable run-time).

The framework presents several requirements. Among them granularity, local parameters used in the decision process, different access rules for different clients, impact no the device must be minimal, the access control must depend on a minimum of other functions and finally, it must provide end-to-end security as well as replay protection.The framework described here is independent of authentification mechanisms, key management or secure transport protocol. In addition to these, it complies to the requirement described by Naetale's paper.

XACML policy evaluation is too heavy a computation, therefore, the solution focuses on the device as an enforcement endpoint rather than a decision one. The local conditions are evaluated on the device to avoid extra messages and delays. Decisons are carried from the external decisions point to the device using assertions and the SAML standard. OAuth was also considered. The framework is comprised of Three entities : a User, a Device and an Authorization Engine. The device owner configures the access policies on the AE which delivers assertions to Users according to these policies. The Users then present the assertions along with its request. A Forth actor, the Resource Directory, facilitate resource discovery.

