When delivering the assertions, the AE may also give the session key to encrypt messages. To prevent replay attacks, the assertions can only be used for a short time after issuance. The device may also store recently used assertions. The implementation uses JWE for assertions



Seitz et al.~\cite{SeitzSelanderGehrmann2013} present a generic authorization
framework with the following features: fine-grained, decision based on local
parameters, no extra messages from the end-device, and a reasonable execution time.

The decision logic is expressed using XACML~\cite{XACML}. XACML policy 
evaluation is too heavy a computation, therefore, the solution focuses on the 
device as an enforcement endpoint (PEP) rather than a decision one (PDP). The 
local conditions are evaluated on the device to avoid extra messages and 
delays. Decisions are carried from the PDP to the device using assertions and 
the SAML standard~\cite{SAML}. OAuth 2.0~\cite{OAuth2} was also considered.

As shown on Figure~\ref{seitz}, the framework is comprised of three entities: a
User, a Device and an Authorization Engine (AE). The device owner configures the
access policies on the AE which delivers assertions to Users according to these 
policies. The User then present the assertions along with its request. A Forth 
actor, the Resource Directory, facilitate resource discovery. 

The underlying protocol is CoAp~\cite{CoAp} used 
with DTLS~\cite{DTLS}. When delivering the assertions, the AE may also give the 
session key to encrypt messages. To prevent replay attacks, the assertions can 
only be used for a short time after issuance. The device may also store 
recently 
used assertions. The implementation uses JWE~\cite{JWE} for assertions.

The discovery system allows the User to request its assertion from the AE without
first referring to the Device. The assertion is sent with the request for 
evaluation. This means no extra messages are needed. The requests concern 
resources on the device rather than the Device itself, meaning the solution is 
fine-grained. 

The token containing the assertion is single use. A new one must be requested 
for each new interaction, this doubles the number of messages required of the 
Subject. In addition, the assertions have a short lifespan and should be 
requested right before access. 

This short life means that, once pushed to the AE, permission update take effect
with only a small delay. The solution is replay-proof and requires both ends to 
mutual authenticate.

This solution is used as a frame of reference by Cherkaoui et 
al.~\cite{cherkaoui:ujm-01011300}. This second article focuses on the physical 
aspect of the IoT. It presents Physical Uncloneable Functions (PUF)
[CITATION NEEDED] as a mean to generate and protect the keys used to secure communication.
PUF uses the unique physical characteristics of a device to produce a secret key
that is unique, random, reliable and tamper resistant. PUF are also a low cost
solution.

The authors then discuss the use of embedded SIM (eSIM). Because an IoT device 
can outlast the lifetime of the SIM card that it uses for communication, the 
problem of replacing this card or provisioning it with information from a new 
provider arises. eSIM are introduced as a way to circumvent this issue.

This second article brings a solution to issues such as key provisioning or 
resistance to physical tampering that appeared as requirements 
in~\cite{SeitzSelanderGehrmann2013} but were not resolved.},
