@Article{zyskind2015enigma,
  author    = {Zyskind, Guy and Nathan, Oz and Pentland, Alex},
  title     = {Enigma: Decentralized computation platform with guaranteed privacy},
  journal   = {arXiv preprint arXiv:1506.03471},
  year      = {2015},
  abstract  = {A peer-to-peer network, enabling different parties to jointly store and run compu-
tations on data while keeping the data completely private. Enigma’s computational
model is based on a highly optimized version of secure multi-party computation,
guaranteed by a verifiable secret-sharing scheme.   For storage,  we use a modi-
fied distributed hashtable for holding secret-shared data.  An external blockchain
is utilized as the controller of the network, manages access control, identities and
serves as a tamper-proof log of events. Security deposits and fees incentivize oper-
ation, correctness and fairness of the system. Similar to Bitcoin, Enigma removes
the need for a trusted third party, enabling autonomous control of personal data.
For the first time, users are able to share their data with cryptographic guarantees
regarding their privacy.},
  comment   = {Privacy : uses secure multi-party computation so no access to data, only fragments
Scalability : unlike BC, each node does not have a replica of the data, only a small set is involved in each calculation. So reduced redundancy.

Enigma offload heavy computations to an off BC network. It uses private contracts instead of public smart contracts. The scripting language is Turing complete. On BC, code is decentralized but not distributed. Enigma has a distributed hash-table accessible through the BC for storage purposes. It can also run heavy computations and then publish proof of correctness on the BC. state of the art MPC can guarantee correctness with dishonest majority (SPDZ). The shares of the SPDZ protocol are published on the BC. This guarantees accountability and correctness. To optimize the network usage, a set of nodes is selected at "random", taking into account reputation and load-balancing. To avoid collusion, the computation can be subdivised into simpler components. Each component is computed by a different set, the intermediary results becoming the inputs for each subsequent set of nodes. 

Data are stored and accessed in 3 distinct ways. Through the BC, where everything is public and all nodes have the same state. Through the DHT where data should be encrypted locally before storage and access can be restricted using a predicate. Using MPC.

A big chunk of the article is dedicated to showing results in the field of MPC communications

Incentive : Nodes are compensated by fees for providing a service. Upon registration, full nodes must make a security deposit. If they miss behave, their deposit is split amonst honest nodes and the computation continues without them. Computation fees are divided amongst node that participated in the computation based on their participation (rounds of computation they performed). The fee cannot always be calculated in advance (because Turing complete. A certain threshhold is needed for the computation to go through. Nodes also take fees for storage. These are market based and time limited. The fees are paid using contract. When a contract expires, it is renewed unless the account balance of the requesting party is too low. In which case, (s)he has a limited time to pay, after which the data are deleted.},
