  organization = {IEEE},
  comment      = {Ashibani et al.'s solution~\cite{ashibani2017context} focuses on authentication.
Classical authentication mechanisms are augmented by contextual information 
gathered on the user. Confidence levels are assigned by a central administrator 
to all available authentication factors. Such factors can be a user's profile, 
its location or historical information. Access is then dependent on the 
confidence level reached by the user's authentication.

If the owner of a smart home considers being actually inside the house is a 
mandatory condition to be able to interact with its devices, then the location 
parameter will be given a high confidence level. If he'd rather not be disturbed
during the night, time will be given more importance.

The paper describes the registration of a user, the validation of this new user's 
participation by the administrator, the completion of its profile over time with
new information such as the device used for logging in or an access pattern. 
The access level of a user is continuously re-calculated based on available 
information.

Every access request must go through a gateway. That gateway is in charge of 
computing every user's access level and grants access based on policies defined 
by the administrator. The devices themselves have no access control logic of 
their own.

This highly centralized approach is a huge hindrance to the scalability of this
solution, as every single access request must go through a single gateway. 
Another issue is the need for the administrator to validate every new user's 
participation. 
However, in the context of a smart home, the number of users and therefore the 
number of simultaneous requests is relatively small.

On the other hand, the system is highly usable. Most of the contextual 
information are gathered without the user's intervention, so the added layer of
security does not affect the user's experience.

Revocation is implicit with the expiration of authentication. Access attempts are
logged encrypted to build the user's profile. No delegation mechanism is described.},
